✅ 1. What is a Model? (Architecture + Weights)
Think of a model like a function f(x) that transforms input into output.
Example:
Input: an image
Output: "cat" or "dog"

To do this, a model has two key components:

✅ 1. Architecture — the design / blueprint
This defines how the model is structured.
Examples:
How many layers?
What type of layers? (Dense, Convolutional, Attention, RNN, etc.)
How data flows through layers?

Analogy:
Architecture is like the shape of a building — number of floors, layout, connections.

✅ 2. Weights — the learned values
Weights are numbers inside the model that get updated during training.

They capture patterns.
After training, weights are what make the model "smart".
Bigger or deeper models mean more weights.

Analogy:
Weights are the furniture inside the building that gets arranged based on experience.

✅ 2. Training vs Inference
✅ Training
This is the learning phase.

You show the model lots of example data.
It predicts → makes mistakes → adjusts weights.
This cycle continues for multiple epochs (passes through data).

You need GPU/TPU for training.

✅ Inference
This is the usage phase.

Model is already trained.
You only feed input → get output.
No learning happens here.
Much cheaper than training.

You usually need CPU or sometimes GPU (for speed).

✅ 3. Tensors (Basic Idea)
Tensor = an n-dimensional array.
You already know:

Scalar → single number
Vector → 1D array
Matrix → 2D array

A tensor extends this idea to N dimensions.
Examples:

Image → 3D tensor (height × width × channels)
Batch of images → 4D tensor

Why ML uses tensors?
Because GPU operations (matrix multiplications) are extremely fast when data is in tensor format.

✅ 4. Overfitting vs Underfitting
✅ Overfitting — model memorizes

Performs well on training data
Performs poorly on new data
Means: too complex for the amount of data

Analogy:
A student memorizes past exam answers instead of understanding concepts.

✅ Underfitting — model doesn’t learn enough

Performs poorly on both training & testing data
Means: model is too simple or not trained enough

Analogy:
A student didn't even study enough to learn basics.

✅ 5. Batch Size, Epochs, Learning Rate
These are core training parameters you will see in ML pipelines (MLflow, Kubeflow, SageMaker, Azure ML).

✅ 1. Batch Size
How many samples you feed into the model at once.
Example:

Dataset size = 10,000 images
Batch size = 100
100 images are processed at a time

Trade-off:

Small batch → slower but more accurate
Large batch → faster but may generalize poorly


✅ 2. Epoch
1 epoch = model sees the entire dataset once.
If you run:
epochs = 10

It means the model will see your whole dataset 10 times during training.

✅ 3. Learning Rate
How big the steps are when updating weights.
Think of it like the speed of learning:

High LR → fast learning, but risks overshooting (unstable)
Low LR → slow but stable learning

Most important hyperparameter in ML.

