 core evaluation metrics in machine learning, especially for classification models.

🎯 First: Understand the Confusion Matrix
All three metrics come from this:
✅ Terms:

TP (True Positive) → predicted YES, actually YES
TN (True Negative) → predicted NO, actually NO
FP (False Positive) → predicted YES, actually NO
FN (False Negative) → predicted NO, actually YES

✅ 1. Accuracy
👉 Definition:
Out of all predictions, how many were correct?

Accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)

✅ Example:
100 samples
90 correct predictions
👉 Accuracy = 90%

✅ 2. Precision
👉 Definition:
Out of all predicted YES, how many are actually YES?

Precision = TP / (TP + FP)

✅ Meaning:
👉 “When the model says YES, how often is it correct?”

✅ Example:

Model predicted 50 patients as sick
Only 40 are actually sick
👉 Precision = 40 / 50 = 80%

✅ When important:
Fraud detection
Spam detection
👉 You want:
❌ Fewer false positives

✅ 3. Recall (Sensitivity)
👉 Definition:
Out of all actual YES, how many did we correctly detect?
Recall = TP / (TP + FN)
✅ Meaning:
👉 “Out of real positives, how many did we catch?”

✅ Example:
100 actual sick people
Model detects 80

👉 Recall = 80%
✅ When important:
Disease detection
Safety systems

👉 You want:
❌ Fewer false negatives

⚖️ Precision vs Recall (Key Insigh)

Metric           Focus     
Precision       Avoid false alarms (FP)
Recall           Don’t miss real cases (FN)

How can we increase accuracy of the model?

“Improving model accuracy is primarily driven by better data quality and feature engineering rather than just changing algorithms.
We ensure high-quality input by performing data cleaning and validation, then create meaningful features to improve model learning.
We also handle class imbalance, perform hyperparameter tuning using Azure ML sweep jobs, and validate models using cross-validation. 
Additionally, we experiment with multiple algorithms like
Random Forest or XGBoost and deploy the best-performing model. In production, continuous monitoring and retraining are used to maintain accuracy over time.”
